        <div class="repair-title">Brentwood (LA County) · Vent-A-Hood Wall Chimney Hood</div>
        <h3>"Fan barely working, almost no suction even on high"</h3>
        <p>Severely clogged grease filter plus a partially seized blower wheel. The filter hadn't been cleaned in over a year, it was coated with solidified grease and nearly opaque. The reduced airflow had also caused grease to build up on the blower wheel itself, adding weight and imbalance. The motor was intact and fully functional.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Removed and deep-cleaned both grease filters (soaked in hot water and degreaser, not dishwasher-safe on this model). Removed the blower wheel assembly and cleaned grease buildup from all blades. Reinstalled and tested, full suction restored on all three speeds. Motor replaced was not needed. Advised customer on 2-month cleaning cycle given the cooking volume in this kitchen.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Beverly Hills (LA County) · Zephyr AK7500BS Island Hood</div>
        <h3>"Makes a horrible grinding sound, started about a month ago"</h3>
        <p>Fan motor bearing failure on a Zephyr island hood, the grinding sound was coming from the motor itself, audible from the adjacent living room. The motor had been running with failing bearings for some time before the noise became loud enough for the homeowner to notice. Left another few weeks, the motor would have seized entirely.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced fan motor assembly with OEM Zephyr part. Cleaned blower wheel while the motor was out, had some grease accumulation. Tested all three fan speeds and light functions post-repair. Noise completely eliminated. Customer was relieved, they'd been cooking with kitchen windows open to avoid the noise.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (Orange County) · GE Under-Cabinet JV536DWW</div>
        <h3>"Hood completely dead, nothing works, no lights, no fan"</h3>
        <p>Blown thermal fuse, the safety fuse inside the hood had tripped due to excessive heat from a severely clogged filter. The filter was so restricted that heat from cooking had nowhere to go and the internal temperature exceeded the fuse rating. This is the less common but more serious consequence of filter neglect, a $15 thermal fuse failure that shuts down the entire unit. Coastal Newport Beach kitchens with high-volume cooking accelerate filter saturation faster than dry inland environments.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced thermal fuse with correct-spec replacement, cleaned filter thoroughly, verified all functions restored. Explained to customer how the failure chain worked, dirty filter → heat buildup → fuse trip, so they understood why filter maintenance actually matters. Unit fully operational within 40 minutes.</div>
      </div>

